Given an integer array `nums`, move all the even integers at the beginning of the array followed by all the odd integers.

Return ***any array** that satisfies this condition*.

**Example 1:**

```
Input: nums = [3,1,2,4]
Output: [2,4,3,1]
Explanation: The outputs [4,2,3,1], [2,4,1,3], and [4,2,1,3] would also be accepted.
```

**Example 2:**

```
Input: nums = [0]
Output: [0]
```

**Constraints:**

- `1 <= nums.length <= 5000`
- `0 <= nums[i] <= 5000`

### Approach (Two Pointers)

- Goal: place **even numbers first**, **odd numbers later**.
- Use two pointers:
    - `i` starts from the left
    - `j` starts from the right
- Swap when:
    - left is odd **and**
    - right is even
- Move pointers based on parity to avoid unnecessary swaps.

## Solution

```java
class Solution {
    public int[] sortArrayByParity(int[] nums) {

        int i = 0, j = nums.length - 1; // two pointers

        // Continue until pointers meet
        while (i < j) {

            int mod1 = nums[i] % 2; // parity of left element
            int mod2 = nums[j] % 2; // parity of right element

            // If left is odd and right is even, swap
            if (mod1 == 1 && mod2 == 0) {
                int temp = nums[i];
                nums[i] = nums[j];
                nums[j] = temp;
            }

            // Move left pointer if element is even
            if (mod1 == 0) {
                i++;
            }

            // Move right pointer if element is odd
            if (mod2 == 1) {
                j--;
            }
        }

        return nums;
    }
}
```

## Time & Space Complexity

| **Time Complexity** | `O(n)` |
| **Space Complexity** | `O(1)` |
